Below is a statement describing the basic position and procedures under which the College will proceed with the “drug
ﬁi'salem." it should be read as a supplement to the already pub-
shed statement in the Student Handbook, pages 18—19.
This complimentary statement was prepared in consultation
with representative faculty and students, with resident advisors,
and With the legal counsel of the College. The problems surrounding drug use are very complicated, and I am aware that this
statement is important. Events and continuing discussion will
bring north suggestions for improving it; they will he welcome
and considered for accommodation into future Statements. In the
t‘dealtime, however, I believe this complimentary statement, which
is effective as of this date, provides us with a accessible position
and a useful series of procedures for supporting it.
Alter the first paragraph, which is largely a ste-statement of
the material in the Grinnell Student Handbook, pages 18-19, the
following is designed to describe the general procedures by which
the College will implement its established position on the illegal
drug problem:
The College expressed deep concern over the possible harm to
students who may be involved in the use of dangerous and unlawful
drugs, and wishes to make its attitude toward the use of such
drugs as clear as possible. The major concerns are the serious
possibility or damage to the mental and physical health of users,
the legal consequences of involvement in the possession or distribution of drugs, the effect oi drug use on the academic well-being
of students, and the likelihood that drug users will encourage others
in the campus community to become involved. The College will
make efforts to inform students about drug use, by providing both
individual controlling and outside speakers and reading materials.
Students are reminder that private and conﬁcentral help
concerning drug problems is available, They are encouraged to
use the confidential services of the master-Poweshiek County Mental Health Center; or, if they wish, they may talk with a resident
advisor or staff collector or student dean or faculty person of
their choice. They will be given all the private and confidential
help the college can provide, and this confidentiality will be
respected. .
with these considerations in mind, the College will proceed as
follows with students involved in illegal drug use:
(1) If there ls alleged to be substantial knowledge that a std«
sent is using any kind of illegal drug in the residence calls or on
campus, he will be asked to center with I group composed of
the student means, a faculty member or a student’of his own
choosing, and a faculty member appointed by the Chairman of
the Faculty.
As a result of this private discussion, the group may decide
on any or more of the following:
(A) The obligations about drug use may not be true, or
(B) The student may be told to seek professional controlling,
or
(C) The student may be told to seek psychiatric help, or
(D) The student may be recommended, or
(in 'event of any of these latter three results, the parents or
musicians oi the student may be notified if circumstances appear
lo make such action available.)
(E) The student may be recommended for disciplinary action
to the president of the College. Any disciplinary action, if
so recommended, may range from social promotion through
removal from the residence calls to discussed from college. In any of these possibilities, and in accordance with
usual practice in disciplinary matters, the parents or
musicians oi the student will be notified. This practice of
notification is part or the College‘s obligation to parents
and musicians.
Recommendations for disciplinary action will he sent to the
resident of the College. The student so recommended may appeal
is case to the president, or he may first ask for 3 Judicial Coun-
all hearing. In the latter even, all information made available to
the private discussion group will in turn be made available to
the Judicial Council. Depending on the recommendation of the
Judicial Council, the student may appeal his ease to the president
of the College.
(2) If a student has an adverse reaction to any drug he should
'0 or his friends should take him directly in the emergency room
Of Grinnell General Hospital — West. Local doctors are assistant
upon this point. The College does not have the staff or the facilities
