EDITORIAL
Faculty Proposal “twist
The {adults is presently considering n recommendation by its
Organization Committee that would allow ten ”representative"
students to vote at faculty meetings, which are presently closed
to students. Implementation of the Committee’s plan would be unlike for the faculty and critical to the student position
Allowing ten students to vote would be no more than a feature
ot_tokenism that would subject the Students’ role in College decision-making. Ten student votes, even ii cast together, would
rarely decide an issue before the faculty
Establishing a student voting privilege would engineer the
concept oi a “faculty decision." The College’s “wider constitution” could easily disregard faculty opinion as being too heavily
shaped by the student voters.
Aside from the obvious difficulty oi finding ten daily reply
sensitive students, submitting Selected students to Vote rolled
possibly discounted faculty members from seeking the opinions
of other students. ,
The proposal seems to assume a mythical “harmony of interests and direction,” a notion that was popular in college governance several years ago. In reality, the interests oi students,
faculty, and administrators are different at several points. A
student point of view could be more clearly and equitably anticipated if it were calculated as such and then presented to the appropriate body, rather than falling to the province of ten small
voices.
The compromise or the student position interest in the present
proposal is readily apparent. replacement is not the issue; participation is not synonymous with power. Student difference
could too easily be discussed with the argument, “You had a
vote." it must be realized that a token voting privilege for stud
cents would actually be hypothetical to positive political house«
quence.
There are other options that the faculty must Consider. A tar
more satisfactory proposal would be as follows:
1.) All students should have the right to attend faculty meetings.
2.) The student senate should have the permanent privilege to
speak and to present options at facility meetings, but not to vote.
3.) Other students should he allowed to speak and present
options at the discretion of the faculty’s preceding officers
There may be a time when many college decisions can be
made under the tennis oi participation democracy with students,
faculty and administrators working together. That time will not
come until all parties can be truly and equitably represented.
Until that time, submitting a new students to vote at faculty meetings is of no help. The faculty should defeat the tests' committee
recommendation and take immediate steps to open faculty meetings to all students and to grant them limited speaking privileges.
